Following, Section 3.1 describes how the compression/de-compression times are calculated, and Section 3.2
presents a brief description of the SIMCAN simulation platform is provided.
3.1. Obtaining compression information
Initially, a thorough analysis of the diÔ¨Äerent compression algorithms must be performed. This analysis consists
in executing a synthetic benchmark for calculating the time required for compressing/decompressing data using
diÔ¨Äerent algorithms. In our previous work [13], we have found that a message has three main properties that
aÔ¨Äect the performance of compressing/decompressing data: message size; datatype of each message element; and
redundancy level of message data.
Therefore, the benchmark studies the algorithm complexity and the amount of compression for each compressor with diÔ¨Äerent types of data, buÔ¨Äer sizes, and redundancy levels. This benchmark has been evaluated in our
cluster with 22 nodes. Each node is Dual-Core Intel(R) Xeon(R) CPU with 4 GB of RAM. The data sets used
have been generated synthetically. Each dataset contains buÔ¨Äers with diÔ¨Äerent properties:
‚Ä¢ Datatype (integer, Ô¨Çoating-point, and double precession).
‚Ä¢ BuÔ¨Äer size: The buÔ¨Äer sizes considered are 100 KB, 500 KB, 800 KB, and 1500 KB for integer and Ô¨Çoatingpoint datasets.
‚Ä¢ Redundancy levels: 0%, 25%, 50%, 75%, and 100%. If the buÔ¨Äer redundancy level is 0%, it means that all
values are diÔ¨Äerent. But, if the redundancy level is 100%, it means that all values are equal to zero. These
entries are randomly distributed among the buÔ¨Äer memory map.
3.2. Overview of the SIMCAN simulation platform
SIMCAN is a simulation platform oriented towards analyzing and studying parallel applications on distributed
systems [20]. SIMCAN has been designed targeting to provide Ô¨Çexibility, accuracy, performance, and scalability,
which makes it a powerful simulation platform for designing, testing and analyzing both actual and non-existent
architectures. The range of systems to simulate comes from a single computing node to a complete high performance distributed system. In fact, this simulation platform has been applied to data systems simulation in the
EPCC art Edinburgh University [21].
The SIMCAN project was initiated in 2008 and it was released as open source software. It is currently available
at ‚Äúhttp://www.arcos.inf.uc3m.es/‚àºSIMCAN‚Äù. A thorough validation process of the proposed simulation platform
has been fulÔ¨Ålled by comparing the results obtained in real architectures with those obtained in the analogous
simulated environments. Those experiments have been achieved in two diÔ¨Äerent real-world scenarios using three
diÔ¨Äerent applications: the IOZone benchmark, the mppTest suite, and BIPS3D [20].

235

236

Alberto N√∫√±ez et al. / Procedia Computer Science 18 (2013) 230 ‚Äì 239

SIMCAN provides a GUI to create and manage large simulation scenarios easily and quickly (see Figure 2).
This GUI is targeted to manage and generate models for the SIMCAN simulation platform. The main goal of this
GUI is two-fold. First, hiding all low-level details, including the language used for implementing components and
creating simulated environments. Second, to ease the generation and customization of distributed system models.

